00:30:42.080 --> 00:30:45.660
so that you put together a strong application

506
00:30:45.700 --> 00:30:49.260
coherently using simple language, and

507
00:30:49.360 --> 00:30:52.780
yet emphasizing and highlighting your research project.

508
00:30:53.680 --> 00:30:57.360
Really, a strong research strategy is the heart of your

509
00:30:57.370 --> 00:31:00.760
application, and help reviewers

510
00:31:00.800 --> 00:31:04.750
understand and appreciate the significance, innovation, and the feasibility

511
00:31:05.080 --> 00:31:05.800
of your research.

512
00:31:06.640 --> 00:31:10.610
And definitely align the application components with

513
00:31:10.640 --> 00:31:11.600
the review criteria.

514
00:31:14.100 --> 00:31:17.820
So currently, NIH and NCI follow a

515
00:31:17.830 --> 00:31:21.320
simplified review framework where your

516
00:31:21.360 --> 00:31:25.179
project or your application is scored on three factors.

517
00:31:25.280 --> 00:31:28.560
Factor one is evaluated for the importance of research,

518
00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:30.860
where the reviewers are

519
00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:34.220
looking at the innovation,

520
00:31:35.140 --> 00:31:38.740
significance, and the novelty of the question that you're asking,

521
00:31:39.260 --> 00:31:42.760
so that at the end, your research must address a meaningful

522
00:31:42.860 --> 00:31:46.300
question and would contribute something new to the field.

523
00:31:47.350 --> 00:31:48.930
This factor,

524
00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:52.680
it's reviewed as a numerical score.

525
00:31:53.940 --> 00:31:57.820
Factor two is evaluated for rigor and feasibility, where the

526
00:31:57.860 --> 00:32:00.680
reviewers are evaluating your approach

527
00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:02.370
and

528
00:32:04.860 --> 00:32:06.160
the scientific

529
00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:11.040
quality, the quality of the science that you're presenting.

530
00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:15.030
What they're looking for is the study design, methodology, and

531
00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:18.900
analysis are well-reasoned and

532
00:32:18.910 --> 00:32:20.760
appropriate to your project's aims.

533
00:32:21.970 --> 00:32:25.210
They also consider the potential challenges and

534
00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:28.760
strategies that you are addressing in your research

535
00:32:28.820 --> 00:32:29.280
project.

536
00:32:30.350 --> 00:32:33.600
This factor also receives a numerical score.

537
00:32:34.540 --> 00:32:38.400
And finally, factor three is where the expertise and resources are

538
00:32:38.440 --> 00:32:42.320
evaluated. So it's basically the reviewers are looking at the

539
00:32:43.220 --> 00:32:47.060
team of scientists that you have proposed for this research, and

540
00:32:47.100 --> 00:32:51.080
the availability of resources for the fulfillment of the

541
00:32:51.160 --> 00:32:51.480
award.

542
00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:52.970
This

543
00:32:54.240 --> 00:32:57.300
factor is evaluated for sufficiency.

544
00:32:57.360 --> 00:32:58.880
So all three factors

545
00:33:00.460 --> 00:33:04.380
are considered to provide you the

546
00:33:04.420 --> 00:33:06.780
overall impact score. However,

547
00:33:07.740 --> 00:33:08.000
the

548
00:33:09.220 --> 00:33:13.060
score of factor one limits how high your impact

549
00:33:13.120 --> 00:33:13.720
score can be.

550
00:33:14.540 --> 00:33:18.200
Which is to say, if your factor one score

551
00:33:18.440 --> 00:33:22.200
is moderate or low, while factor two is really strong and

552
00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:24.240
factor three is sufficient,

553
00:33:25.470 --> 00:33:29.280
the possibility of your overall score being reflected

554
00:33:29.340 --> 00:33:32.760
by factor one is really high. So do focus

555
00:33:32.960 --> 00:33:35.640
on aiming to get a

556
00:33:35.700 --> 00:33:38.179
exceptional factor one score.

